77.4	Diphtheria	Diphtheria	Diphtheria "pair of leather scrolls") is an upper respiratory tract illness caused by Corynebacterium diphtheriae, a facultative anaerobic, Gram-positive bacterium. It is characterized by sore throat, low fever, and an adherent membrane (a pseudomembrane) on the tonsils, pharynx, and/or nasal cavity. A milder form of diphtheria can be restricted to the skin. Less common consequences include myocarditis (about 20% of cases) and peripheral neuropathy (about 10% of cases).	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a8/Diphtheria_bull_neck.5325_lores.jpg/150px-Diphtheria_bull_neck.5325_lores.jpg
